But it also, much like Pydantic, will do validation when you try and,

00:41:41.010 --> 00:41:45.180
if you use one of its functions to convert raw data, like a dictionary, into this type.

00:41:46.140 --> 00:41:50.880
And much like Pydantic as well, it also gives the ability to take this model

00:41:51.190 --> 00:41:55.020
and turn it into an open API, a JSON schema definition.

00:41:55.270 --> 00:42:00.400
And that's the final thing Quartz schema does is once you've decorated all your roots,

00:42:00.740 --> 00:42:04.740
it will auto-generate an open API definition for you as well.

00:42:06.180 --> 00:42:06.420
It will.

00:42:06.650 --> 00:42:06.780
Okay.

00:42:07.560 --> 00:42:10.920
Yeah, using Swagger slash docs.

00:42:13.220 --> 00:42:13.400
Okay.

00:42:14.820 --> 00:42:15.880
I think that's really nice.

00:42:17.820 --> 00:42:19.260
A lot of APIs just don't.

00:42:19.260 --> 00:42:20.280
They're like, we're not going to do that.

00:42:21.500 --> 00:42:23.540
If they don't have something automated to do it.

00:42:23.760 --> 00:42:29.200
And having typed classes representing all your inbound and outbound data,

00:42:29.410 --> 00:42:30.000
pretty easy, right?

00:42:30.560 --> 00:42:32.680
Yeah, I mean, it really helps with mypy, right?

00:42:32.780 --> 00:42:36.260
Because instead of having your request.data or something like that,

00:42:36.360 --> 00:42:39.700
which is some dict that, as far as mypy concerns, can be anything,

00:42:40.140 --> 00:42:43.040
it must be a to-do instance in this function now.

00:42:43.200 --> 00:42:45.180
So yeah, it really helps with your type checking.

00:42:45.980 --> 00:42:46.500
Yeah, absolutely.

00:42:47.320 --> 00:42:48.260
