00:42:50.200 --> 00:42:54.120
Sock from Miguel Grimberg, Flask WebSocket.

00:42:56.240 --> 00:42:59.280
Yeah, so this one there is an extension for,

00:42:59.360 --> 00:43:02.340
because this is one of the areas that Quart being natively async

00:43:02.480 --> 00:43:03.040
can just do itself.

00:43:04.140 --> 00:43:08.140
So Quart, I think I describe sometimes as a superset of Flask

00:43:08.460 --> 00:43:10.820
because it can do everything Flask can do and a bit more.

00:43:10.820 --> 00:43:11.840
The C++ of Flask.

00:43:13.460 --> 00:43:14.040
Yeah, exactly.

00:43:16.240 --> 00:43:16.440
Awesome.

00:43:18.260 --> 00:43:22.280
So WebSockets kind of solve a problem

00:43:22.400 --> 00:43:24.660
that websites generally have not been able to do.

00:43:24.880 --> 00:43:26.400
Like once you make a request,

00:43:26.660 --> 00:43:28.000
usually there's the response and that's it.

00:43:28.060 --> 00:43:39.080
But what if the server, you want to send more stuff to the server, server wants to send stuff out to you later, like I started this job three seconds later, now it's done or, you know, this bidirectional exchange.

00:43:41.220 --> 00:43:46.380
It's really cool, but a lot of times I feel like it's a little over the top, right?

00:43:46.520 --> 00:43:54.200
Like a lot of times I think people maybe just want push notifications from the server and not true, like let's have a conversation.

00:43:54.380 --> 00:43:57.100
I just need to know when this happens, just let me know as soon as it's done, right?

00:43:57.920 --> 00:43:59.480
Yeah. Go ahead.

00:43:59.720 --> 00:44:00.460
I was going to say,

00:44:01.510 --> 00:44:05.720
server-sent events seem to be not that well-known,

00:44:06.040 --> 00:44:08.940
but probably describe your usage really well.

00:44:09.320 --> 00:44:10.700
That's exactly what I was getting at.

00:44:11.360 --> 00:44:12.840
Does court support SSE?

00:44:12.980 --> 00:44:14.060
Does it support server-sent events?

00:44:14.800 --> 00:44:17.640
Yeah. I think there's an extension for it,

00:44:17.860 --> 00:44:21.400
but in reality, it's a very small bit of code you need.

00:44:24.360 --> 00:44:31.340
I mean, because you literally return a response with a certain header, and then you just return a, well, here we go.

00:44:31.920 --> 00:44:33.720
There's an example in the documentation for court.

00:44:34.600 --> 00:44:37.480
But you just return a certain data structure, and then you've got it.

00:44:38.720 --> 00:44:39.080
Yeah.

00:44:39.170 --> 00:44:43.800
So I think that's, when people say they want WebSockets, I think most of the time this is what they want.

00:44:44.020 --> 00:44:47.840
They want the client, the server to call the client sometimes, not just the other way around.

00:44:48.660 --> 00:44:48.880
Yeah.

00:44:49.140 --> 00:44:52.740
So I'm going to go slightly off topic because it's going to interest me.

00:44:52.860 --> 00:45:04.180
Well, it's related to this, but one of the things I implemented in Hypercorn, because I find it really interesting, is I think two, no, it must be more like four years ago, they introduced WebSockets for HTTP2.

00:45:04.900 --> 00:45:10.520
And of course, one of the reasons you want WebSockets is because the cost of opening a connection for HTTP1 is fairly expensive.

00:45:10.700 --> 00:45:12.540
So you can keep it open and do the bidirectional.

00:45:13.080 --> 00:45:16.200
But with HTTP2, you don't even need an extra connection anymore.

00:45:16.540 --> 00:45:19.900
You can have your WebSocket stream on the same connection as all your requests as well.

00:45:20.320 --> 00:45:21.500
So it's really nice and efficient.

00:45:21.580 --> 00:45:26.940
So, yeah, I'd love to have an opportunity to make more use of it because I find it really interesting.

00:45:27.160 --> 00:45:31.460
But the code I write professionally at the moment doesn't quite need that level of real-time interaction.

00:45:31.780 --> 00:45:32.180
I know.

00:45:32.380 --> 00:45:34.600
All the stuff I built, I'm like, that would be so fun.

00:45:34.780 --> 00:45:36.660
But, you know, I just don't need that.

00:45:37.219 --> 00:45:37.940
Yeah, exactly.

00:45:38.260 --> 00:45:39.120
Just have no use case.

