00:49:07.700 --> 00:49:12.940
Yeah, so this is a very recent release that I haven't announced anywhere else yet.

00:49:13.560 --> 00:49:22.700
But this is something, I think I read a post recently that said, for your web framework, you need like five things.

00:49:22.890 --> 00:49:31.860
Like you need a database connection, you need some kind of validation, input, output, rate limiting, authentication, and you need array to run periodic tasks.

00:49:32.540 --> 00:49:36.180
And in the past, my way to do this was extra infrastructure.

00:49:36.500 --> 00:49:40.040
So it was Cron running somewhere or some kind of, I think,

00:49:40.980 --> 00:49:43.860
CloudWatch to some kind of event generator based on a Cron schedule.

00:49:45.279 --> 00:49:48.760
And for me, that's just annoying because now I have to build extra infrastructure,

00:49:49.420 --> 00:49:50.160
which I don't need.

00:49:50.280 --> 00:49:53.060
Maybe not Celery or RabbitMQ or something like that, right?

00:49:53.640 --> 00:49:54.220
Yeah, exactly.

00:49:54.560 --> 00:49:57.660
But again, with those, you need that extra infrastructure for it to work.

00:49:57.720 --> 00:49:58.600
It's another server.

00:49:58.780 --> 00:50:00.080
It's another thing that could get hacked.

00:50:00.220 --> 00:50:00.940
You've got to patch it.

00:50:01.340 --> 00:50:02.240
You've got to secure it.

00:50:02.340 --> 00:50:03.200
You've got to know how to run it.

00:50:03.440 --> 00:50:06.300
It could go down and then none of your background stuff works anymore.

00:50:06.480 --> 00:50:09.360
it's all a hassle, even though it has a benefit.

00:50:10.400 --> 00:50:10.820
Yeah, yeah.

00:50:11.210 --> 00:50:15.620
So what I really want to do is make use of the async event loop

00:50:16.050 --> 00:50:18.100
and just run a task in the background periodically.

00:50:18.900 --> 00:50:21.000
And obviously, at some point, this will normally scale

00:50:21.210 --> 00:50:23.520
because I have so many background tasks that dominate the server

00:50:23.940 --> 00:50:24.740
and stop it doing requests.

00:50:25.680 --> 00:50:27.140
But while I'm small and starting out,

00:50:27.700 --> 00:50:29.500
this just makes life so much easier.

00:50:30.000 --> 00:50:30.440
Absolutely.

00:50:31.070 --> 00:50:32.720
It totally does.

00:50:33.620 --> 00:50:35.580
And because everything's async and await,

00:50:35.800 --> 00:50:38.580
you can just set up the task and just await the task.

00:50:39.380 --> 00:50:44.060
And it just blends in hopefully well with all the web requests, right?

00:50:44.780 --> 00:50:45.280
Yeah, yeah.

00:50:45.490 --> 00:50:50.160
So for court tasks, if you write your task as an async def,

00:50:50.530 --> 00:50:51.820
then it will run it in the event loop.

00:50:52.310 --> 00:50:55.220
But if you write it as a def, it will run it on a thread.

00:50:55.700 --> 00:50:58.660
So if you have synchronous code that's going to block the event loop,

00:50:59.040 --> 00:51:02.900
like you're using traditional IO for one of the better phrase,

00:51:03.400 --> 00:51:05.360
then if you just use def, it will run it on a task.

00:51:05.580 --> 00:51:07.160
won't block your event loop and you'll be fine.

00:51:07.400 --> 00:51:09.340
So yes, it's nice in that respect.

00:51:10.960 --> 00:51:11.400
Yeah.

00:51:11.500 --> 00:51:18.120
And as long as your async pieces are fine grained enough,

00:51:18.490 --> 00:51:19.300
you probably won't know.

00:51:20.530 --> 00:51:20.680
Right.

00:51:20.840 --> 00:51:20.920
Yeah.

00:51:21.270 --> 00:51:21.380
Yeah.

00:51:22.600 --> 00:51:22.700
Yeah.

00:51:22.740 --> 00:51:23.000
It's just,

00:51:23.110 --> 00:51:27.620
if you run a whole bunch of synchronous code or something like that,

00:51:27.650 --> 00:51:29.200
you might start to clog things up,

00:51:29.320 --> 00:51:30.760
but don't do that.

00:51:33.520 --> 00:51:33.780
Honestly,

00:51:34.040 --> 00:51:34.680
like what you find,

00:51:34.820 --> 00:51:38.520
what I find anyway on the web most of the time is you're talking to other things, talking to a

00:51:38.600 --> 00:51:45.460
database, talking to a cache, talking to an API. All those things are like perfectly suited for

00:51:45.700 --> 00:51:52.180
await because it's most of the time you're almost outside the web app. Yeah, I think the perfect one

00:51:52.260 --> 00:51:58.160
for this that I keep thinking of is when you want to send a periodic email, like a reminder or a

00:51:58.170 --> 00:52:02.679
summary of the day, just write this decorated task run and you have your function that just sends

00:52:02.700 --> 00:52:08.480
emails it's yeah that's why it exists for me it makes that so much easier yeah absolutely

00:52:08.980 --> 00:52:13.160
right yeah like you say just send out a quick email like hey i need to reset my password all right here

00:52:13.160 --> 00:52:17.840
we're going to send you you know call an api like SendGrid or something like that we're going to

00:52:18.240 --> 00:52:24.500
send you but you don't want to block block things up you just kick that onto the background work and

00:52:24.760 --> 00:52:32.660
off it goes so one of the things that people would say all right you guys i know you're excited about

00:52:32.660 --> 00:52:42.020
but we need durability what about what if the server goes down or what if another potential

00:52:42.190 --> 00:52:47.960
issue is what if you scale like at least the cron stuff like what if you fan out your web app into

00:52:48.220 --> 00:52:53.640
like 10 worker processes and you say run in five seconds and they all run in five seconds

00:52:54.420 --> 00:53:00.160
10 times or those kind of issues here.

00:53:01.680 --> 00:53:06.020
So this extension supports a couple of extensions to it.

00:53:06.220 --> 00:53:08.960
So you can pass it a custom store,

00:53:09.380 --> 00:53:12.760
which allows you to store when the task last ran.

00:53:13.180 --> 00:53:14.860
And so that means if the server goes down

00:53:14.920 --> 00:53:16.200
and it misses an invocation,

00:53:16.600 --> 00:53:17.680
then when it comes back up,

00:53:17.700 --> 00:53:19.780
it will recognize that and run the task straight away

00:53:20.180 --> 00:53:21.500
rather than wait till the next time.

00:53:22.420 --> 00:53:29.980
And the other thing it supports is you can decide what should happen before the task starts and what should happen after.

00:53:30.600 --> 00:53:33.780
So this allows you to put some locking in for your second case.

00:53:34.540 --> 00:53:41.180
In both cases, the reason it's not built in to court tasks is you'll need to decide where you store this information, where you store the lock, where do you store the...

00:53:41.300 --> 00:53:43.640
So usually a database works for that.

00:53:43.800 --> 00:53:46.620
So yeah, you can add it all, but you've got to choose how yourself.

00:53:47.300 --> 00:53:51.060
That's cool that it has placeholders and ways to plug that in.

00:53:51.420 --> 00:53:52.260
That's what I was thinking of.

00:53:54.440 --> 00:53:56.960
Instead of just storing it in memory and throwing it on the queue,

00:53:57.760 --> 00:54:01.180
put it into the database and have the task just check the database and go,

